postTitle: The House of Representatives approves on second reading HB 9349, which seeks to reinstitute absolute divorce as an alternative mode for the dissolution of marriage. | via Willard Cheng, ABS-CBN News
text:
In Christianity, divorce is a complex issue. While the Bible acknowledges divorce in certain circumstances, it's generally viewed as a last resort.

In some interpretations of biblical teachings, divorce is permitted in cases of adultery or abandonment (Matthew 19:9). However, reconciliation and forgiveness are encouraged whenever possible.

If reconciliation isn't possible, seeking a divorce may be necessary for both parties to find healing and move forward in their lives. While divorce is a difficult decision, it's crucial to prioritize emotional well-being and seek guidance from trusted spiritual advisors.

Divorce isn't inherently good for kids, but in some cases, it can be a better option than staying in a toxic or unhealthy household. It can provide relief from ongoing conflict, reduce exposure to negative interactions between parents, and create opportunities for children to have more stable and nurturing environments.

Please be open-minded and don't be naive. This bill will not ruin happy families and good marriages. This bill is to give freedom to those who are suffering from abusive marriages. Not for those who are happily married.

𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬 𝐡𝐚𝐬 𝐛𝐞𝐞𝐧 𝐜𝐨𝐧𝐬𝐢𝐝𝐞𝐫𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐢𝐧𝐭𝐫𝐨𝐝𝐮𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐚𝐧 𝐀𝐛𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐞 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐁𝐢𝐥𝐥, 𝐰𝐡𝐢𝐜𝐡 𝐰𝐨𝐮𝐥𝐝 𝐚𝐥𝐥𝐨𝐰 𝐟𝐨𝐫 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐥𝐞𝐠𝐚𝐥 𝐭𝐞𝐫𝐦𝐢𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐚 𝐦𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞 𝐛𝐲 𝐚 𝐜𝐨𝐮𝐫𝐭 𝐢𝐧 𝐚 𝐥𝐞𝐠𝐚𝐥 𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐜𝐞𝐞𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠. 𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐠𝐫𝐨𝐮𝐧𝐝𝐬 𝐟𝐨𝐫 𝐚𝐛𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐮𝐧𝐝𝐞𝐫 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐛𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐢𝐧𝐜𝐥𝐮𝐝𝐞 𝐬𝐢𝐭𝐮𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬 𝐰𝐡𝐞𝐫𝐞 𝐬𝐩𝐨𝐮𝐬𝐞𝐬 𝐡𝐚𝐯𝐞 𝐛𝐞𝐞𝐧 𝐬𝐞𝐩𝐚𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐝 𝐟𝐨𝐫 𝐚𝐭 𝐥𝐞𝐚𝐬𝐭 𝐟𝐢𝐯𝐞 𝐲𝐞𝐚𝐫𝐬 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐫𝐞𝐜𝐨𝐧𝐜𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐢𝐬 𝐡𝐢𝐠𝐡𝐥𝐲 𝐢𝐦𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐛𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞, 𝐨𝐫 𝐢𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞𝐲 𝐡𝐚𝐯𝐞 𝐛𝐞𝐞𝐧 𝐥𝐞𝐠𝐚𝐥𝐥𝐲 𝐬𝐞𝐩𝐚𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐝 𝐛𝐲 𝐥𝐚𝐰.
𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐒𝐞𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐞 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬 𝐡𝐚𝐬 𝐛𝐞𝐞𝐧 𝐢𝐧𝐯𝐨𝐥𝐯𝐞𝐝 𝐢𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐬𝐜𝐮𝐬𝐬𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐀𝐜𝐭 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬, 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐒𝐞𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐞 𝐁𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐍𝐨. 𝟐𝟑𝟕 𝐟𝐢𝐥𝐞𝐝 𝐨𝐧 𝐉𝐮𝐥𝐲 𝟕, 𝟐𝟎𝟐𝟐, 𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐯𝐢𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐟𝐨𝐫 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐬𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐦𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞.
𝐈𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝟏𝟕𝐭𝐡 𝐂𝐨𝐧𝐠𝐫𝐞𝐬𝐬 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐑𝐞𝐩𝐮𝐛𝐥𝐢𝐜, 𝐇𝐨𝐮𝐬𝐞 𝐁𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐍𝐨. 𝟕𝟑𝟎𝟑 𝐰𝐚𝐬 𝐢𝐧𝐭𝐫𝐨𝐝𝐮𝐜𝐞𝐝, 𝐭𝐢𝐭𝐥𝐞𝐝 "𝐀𝐧 𝐀𝐜𝐭 𝐈𝐧𝐬𝐭𝐢𝐭𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐀𝐛𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐞 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐃𝐢𝐬𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐌𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞 𝐢𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬," 𝐚𝐥𝐬𝐨 𝐤𝐧𝐨𝐰𝐧 𝐚𝐬 𝐭𝐡𝐞 "𝐀𝐛𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐞 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐀𝐜𝐭 𝐨𝐟 𝟐𝟎𝟏𝟖."
𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐚𝐩𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐯𝐚𝐥 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐀𝐛𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐞 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐁𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐛𝐲 𝐚 𝐤𝐞𝐲 𝐩𝐚𝐧𝐞𝐥 𝐢𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬 𝐦𝐚𝐫𝐤𝐬 𝐚 𝐬𝐢𝐠𝐧𝐢𝐟𝐢𝐜𝐚𝐧𝐭 𝐬𝐭𝐞𝐩 𝐭𝐨𝐰𝐚𝐫𝐝𝐬 𝐚𝐥𝐢𝐠𝐧𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐜𝐨𝐮𝐧𝐭𝐫𝐲 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐨𝐭𝐡𝐞𝐫𝐬 𝐭𝐡𝐚𝐭 𝐫𝐞𝐜𝐨𝐠𝐧𝐢𝐳𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐚𝐬 𝐚 𝐥𝐞𝐠𝐚𝐥 𝐨𝐩𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧. 𝐓𝐡𝐢𝐬 𝐛𝐢𝐥𝐥, 𝐚𝐥𝐬𝐨 𝐤𝐧𝐨𝐰𝐧 𝐚𝐬 𝐭𝐡𝐞 "𝐃𝐢𝐬𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐌𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞 𝐀𝐜𝐭," 𝐡𝐚𝐬 𝐠𝐚𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐝 𝐞𝐧𝐝𝐨𝐫𝐬𝐞𝐦𝐞𝐧𝐭 𝐟𝐫𝐨𝐦 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐒𝐞𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐞 𝐂𝐨𝐦𝐦𝐢𝐭𝐭𝐞𝐞 𝐨𝐧 𝐖𝐨𝐦𝐞𝐧, 𝐂𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐝𝐫𝐞𝐧, 𝐅𝐚𝐦𝐢𝐥𝐲 𝐑𝐞𝐥𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬, 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐆𝐞𝐧𝐝𝐞𝐫.
𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐢𝐧𝐭𝐫𝐨𝐝𝐮𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐚𝐧 𝐀𝐛𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐞 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐁𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐢𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬 𝐫𝐞𝐟𝐥𝐞𝐜𝐭𝐬 𝐚 𝐬𝐡𝐢𝐟𝐭 𝐭𝐨𝐰𝐚𝐫𝐝𝐬 𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐯𝐢𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐚 𝐥𝐞𝐠𝐚𝐥 𝐟𝐫𝐚𝐦𝐞𝐰𝐨𝐫𝐤 𝐟𝐨𝐫 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐬𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐦𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞𝐬, 𝐨𝐟𝐟𝐞𝐫𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐚𝐧 𝐚𝐥𝐭𝐞𝐫𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐯𝐞 𝐭𝐨 𝐚𝐦𝐞𝐧𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐨𝐫 𝐫𝐞𝐩𝐞𝐚𝐥𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐞𝐱𝐢𝐬𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐥𝐚𝐰𝐬 𝐨𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐬𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐦𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞𝐬.

postTitle: The House of Representatives approves on second reading HB 9349, which seeks to reinstitute absolute divorce as an alternative mode for the dissolution of marriage. | via Willard Cheng, ABS-CBN News

4. 𝑷𝒓𝒐𝒎𝒐𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒐𝒇 𝑬𝒎𝒐𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏𝒂𝒍 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝑴𝒆𝒏𝒕𝒂𝒍 𝑯𝒆𝒂𝒍𝒕𝒉:
 
- 𝑨𝒍𝒍𝒐𝒘𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒇𝒐𝒓 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆 𝒕𝒉𝒓𝒐𝒖𝒈𝒉 𝒂 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝒇𝒓𝒂𝒎𝒆𝒘𝒐𝒓𝒌 𝒄𝒂𝒏 𝒄𝒐𝒏𝒕𝒓𝒊𝒃𝒖𝒕𝒆 𝒕𝒐 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒆𝒎𝒐𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏𝒂𝒍 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒎𝒆𝒏𝒕𝒂𝒍 𝒘𝒆𝒍𝒍-𝒃𝒆𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒐𝒇 𝒊𝒏𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒖𝒂𝒍𝒔 𝒊𝒏 𝒖𝒏𝒉𝒂𝒑𝒑𝒚 𝒐𝒓 𝒂𝒃𝒖𝒔𝒊𝒗𝒆 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒓𝒊𝒂𝒈𝒆𝒔. 𝑰𝒕 𝒆𝒏𝒂𝒃𝒍𝒆𝒔 𝒕𝒉𝒆𝒎 𝒕𝒐 𝒔𝒆𝒆𝒌 𝒄𝒍𝒐𝒔𝒖𝒓𝒆, 𝒎𝒐𝒗𝒆 𝒇𝒐𝒓𝒘𝒂𝒓𝒅, 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒓𝒆𝒃𝒖𝒊𝒍𝒅 𝒕𝒉𝒆𝒊𝒓 𝒍𝒊𝒗𝒆𝒔 𝒊𝒏 𝒂 𝒉𝒆𝒂𝒍𝒕𝒉𝒊𝒆𝒓 𝒆𝒏𝒗𝒊𝒓𝒐𝒏𝒎𝒆𝒏𝒕.

5. 𝑺𝒐𝒄𝒊𝒂𝒍 𝑷𝒓𝒐𝒈𝒓𝒆𝒔𝒔 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝑮𝒆𝒏𝒅𝒆𝒓 𝑬𝒒𝒖𝒂𝒍𝒊𝒕𝒚:
 
- 𝑻𝒉𝒆 𝒊𝒏𝒕𝒓𝒐𝒅𝒖𝒄𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒐𝒇 𝒂 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆 𝒃𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒓𝒆𝒇𝒍𝒆𝒄𝒕𝒔 𝒔𝒐𝒄𝒊𝒂𝒍 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒈𝒓𝒆𝒔𝒔 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒎𝒐𝒕𝒆𝒔 𝒈𝒆𝒏𝒅𝒆𝒓 𝒆𝒒𝒖𝒂𝒍𝒊𝒕𝒚 𝒃𝒚 𝒓𝒆𝒄𝒐𝒈𝒏𝒊𝒛𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒕𝒉𝒂𝒕 𝒊𝒏𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒖𝒂𝒍𝒔, 𝒆𝒔𝒑𝒆𝒄𝒊𝒂𝒍𝒍𝒚 𝒘𝒐𝒎𝒆𝒏, 𝒔𝒉𝒐𝒖𝒍𝒅 𝒏𝒐𝒕 𝒃𝒆 𝒕𝒓𝒂𝒑𝒑𝒆𝒅 𝒊𝒏 𝒂𝒃𝒖𝒔𝒊𝒗𝒆 𝒐𝒓 𝒖𝒏𝒉𝒂𝒑𝒑𝒚 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒓𝒊𝒂𝒈𝒆𝒔. 𝑰𝒕 𝒆𝒎𝒑𝒐𝒘𝒆𝒓𝒔 𝒊𝒏𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒖𝒂𝒍𝒔 𝒕𝒐 𝒔𝒆𝒆𝒌 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝒓𝒆𝒎𝒆𝒅𝒊𝒆𝒔 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒕𝒆𝒄𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒇𝒓𝒐𝒎 𝒉𝒂𝒓𝒎𝒇𝒖𝒍 𝒓𝒆𝒍𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏𝒔𝒉𝒊𝒑𝒔.

6. 𝑷𝒓𝒆𝒗𝒆𝒏𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒐𝒇 𝑳𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝑳𝒐𝒐𝒑𝒉𝒐𝒍𝒆𝒔:
 
- 𝑯𝒂𝒗𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒂 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆 𝒃𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒉𝒆𝒍𝒑𝒔 𝒑𝒓𝒆𝒗𝒆𝒏𝒕 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝒍𝒐𝒐𝒑𝒉𝒐𝒍𝒆𝒔 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒇𝒓𝒂𝒖𝒅𝒖𝒍𝒆𝒏𝒕 𝒑𝒓𝒂𝒄𝒕𝒊𝒄𝒆𝒔 𝒊𝒏 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒅𝒊𝒔𝒔𝒐𝒍𝒖𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒐𝒇 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒓𝒊𝒂𝒈𝒆𝒔. 𝑰𝒕 𝒆𝒔𝒕𝒂𝒃𝒍𝒊𝒔𝒉𝒆𝒔 𝒄𝒍𝒆𝒂𝒓 𝒈𝒖𝒊𝒅𝒆𝒍𝒊𝒏𝒆𝒔 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒄𝒓𝒊𝒕𝒆𝒓𝒊𝒂 𝒇𝒐𝒓 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆, 𝒓𝒆𝒅𝒖𝒄𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒑𝒐𝒕𝒆𝒏𝒕𝒊𝒂𝒍 𝒇𝒐𝒓 𝒂𝒃𝒖𝒔𝒆 𝒐𝒓 𝒎𝒂𝒏𝒊𝒑𝒖𝒍𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒐𝒇 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝒔𝒚𝒔𝒕𝒆𝒎.
 
𝑶𝒗𝒆𝒓𝒂𝒍𝒍, 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒆𝒔𝒔𝒆𝒏𝒄𝒆 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒊𝒎𝒑𝒐𝒓𝒕𝒂𝒏𝒄𝒆 𝒐𝒇 𝒉𝒂𝒗𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒂 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆 𝒃𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒊𝒏 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝑷𝒉𝒊𝒍𝒊𝒑𝒑𝒊𝒏𝒆𝒔 𝒓𝒆𝒗𝒐𝒍𝒗𝒆 𝒂𝒓𝒐𝒖𝒏𝒅 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒂 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝒂𝒗𝒆𝒏𝒖𝒆 𝒇𝒐𝒓 𝒄𝒐𝒖𝒑𝒍𝒆𝒔 𝒕𝒐 𝒆𝒏𝒅 𝒊𝒓𝒓𝒆𝒕𝒓𝒊𝒆𝒗𝒂𝒃𝒍𝒚 𝒃𝒓𝒐𝒌𝒆𝒏 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒓𝒊𝒂𝒈𝒆𝒔, 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒕𝒆𝒄𝒕𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒊𝒏𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒖𝒂𝒍𝒔' 𝒓𝒊𝒈𝒉𝒕𝒔, 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒎𝒐𝒕𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒆𝒎𝒐𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏𝒂𝒍 𝒘𝒆𝒍𝒍-𝒃𝒆𝒊𝒏𝒈, 𝒂𝒅𝒗𝒂𝒏𝒄𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒔𝒐𝒄𝒊𝒂𝒍 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒈𝒓𝒆𝒔𝒔, 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒑𝒓𝒆𝒗𝒆𝒏𝒕𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝒂𝒎𝒃𝒊𝒈𝒖𝒊𝒕𝒊𝒆𝒔 𝒊𝒏 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒅𝒊𝒔𝒔𝒐𝒍𝒖𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒐𝒇 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒊𝒕𝒂𝒍 𝒓𝒆𝒍𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏𝒔𝒉𝒊𝒑𝒔.

postTitle: The House of Representatives approves on second reading HB 9349, which seeks to reinstitute absolute divorce as an alternative mode for the dissolution of marriage. | via Willard Cheng, ABS-CBN News
text:
𝑻𝒉𝒆 𝒆𝒔𝒔𝒆𝒏𝒄𝒆 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒊𝒎𝒑𝒐𝒓𝒕𝒂𝒏𝒄𝒆 𝒐𝒇 𝒉𝒂𝒗𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒂 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆 𝒃𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒊𝒏 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝑷𝒉𝒊𝒍𝒊𝒑𝒑𝒊𝒏𝒆𝒔 𝒍𝒊𝒆 𝒊𝒏 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒂 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝒇𝒓𝒂𝒎𝒆𝒘𝒐𝒓𝒌 𝒕𝒉𝒂𝒕 𝒓𝒆𝒄𝒐𝒈𝒏𝒊𝒛𝒆𝒔 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒂𝒅𝒅𝒓𝒆𝒔𝒔𝒆𝒔 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒄𝒐𝒎𝒑𝒍𝒆𝒙𝒊𝒕𝒊𝒆𝒔 𝒐𝒇 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒊𝒕𝒂𝒍 𝒓𝒆𝒍𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏𝒔𝒉𝒊𝒑𝒔 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒐𝒇𝒇𝒆𝒓𝒔 𝒂 𝒇𝒐𝒓𝒎𝒂𝒍 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒄𝒆𝒔𝒔 𝒇𝒐𝒓 𝒄𝒐𝒖𝒑𝒍𝒆𝒔 𝒕𝒐 𝒅𝒊𝒔𝒔𝒐𝒍𝒗𝒆 𝒕𝒉𝒆𝒊𝒓 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒓𝒊𝒂𝒈𝒆 𝒘𝒉𝒆𝒏 𝒓𝒆𝒄𝒐𝒏𝒄𝒊𝒍𝒊𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒊𝒔 𝒏𝒐 𝒍𝒐𝒏𝒈𝒆𝒓 𝒇𝒆𝒂𝒔𝒊𝒃𝒍𝒆. 𝑺𝒐𝒎𝒆 𝒌𝒆𝒚 𝒑𝒐𝒊𝒏𝒕𝒔 𝒉𝒊𝒈𝒉𝒍𝒊𝒈𝒉𝒕𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒆𝒔𝒔𝒆𝒏𝒄𝒆 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒊𝒎𝒑𝒐𝒓𝒕𝒂𝒏𝒄𝒆 𝒐𝒇 𝒉𝒂𝒗𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒂 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆 𝒃𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒊𝒏 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝑷𝒉𝒊𝒍𝒊𝒑𝒑𝒊𝒏𝒆𝒔 𝒊𝒏𝒄𝒍𝒖𝒅𝒆:
 
1. 𝑳𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝑹𝒆𝒄𝒐𝒈𝒏𝒊𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒐𝒇 𝑴𝒂𝒓𝒊𝒕𝒂𝒍 𝑫𝒊𝒔𝒔𝒐𝒍𝒖𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏:
 
- 𝑨 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆 𝒃𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒂𝒄𝒌𝒏𝒐𝒘𝒍𝒆𝒅𝒈𝒆𝒔 𝒕𝒉𝒂𝒕 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒓𝒊𝒂𝒈𝒆𝒔 𝒄𝒂𝒏 𝒊𝒓𝒓𝒆𝒕𝒓𝒊𝒆𝒗𝒂𝒃𝒍𝒚 𝒃𝒓𝒆𝒂𝒌 𝒅𝒐𝒘𝒏, 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒕𝒉𝒆𝒓𝒆 𝒊𝒔 𝒂 𝒏𝒆𝒆𝒅 𝒇𝒐𝒓 𝒂 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝒎𝒆𝒄𝒉𝒂𝒏𝒊𝒔𝒎 𝒕𝒐 𝒇𝒐𝒓𝒎𝒂𝒍𝒍𝒚 𝒆𝒏𝒅 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒊𝒕𝒂𝒍 𝒓𝒆𝒍𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏𝒔𝒉𝒊𝒑. 𝑰𝒕 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒆𝒔 𝒂 𝒔𝒕𝒓𝒖𝒄𝒕𝒖𝒓𝒆𝒅 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒄𝒆𝒔𝒔 𝒇𝒐𝒓 𝒄𝒐𝒖𝒑𝒍𝒆𝒔 𝒕𝒐 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍𝒍𝒚 𝒔𝒆𝒑𝒂𝒓𝒂𝒕𝒆 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒎𝒐𝒗𝒆 𝒐𝒏 𝒘𝒊𝒕𝒉 𝒕𝒉𝒆𝒊𝒓 𝒍𝒊𝒗𝒆𝒔.

2. 𝑷𝒓𝒐𝒕𝒆𝒄𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒐𝒇 𝑰𝒏𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒖𝒂𝒍𝒔' 𝑹𝒊𝒈𝒉𝒕𝒔:
 
- 𝑯𝒂𝒗𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒂 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆 𝒃𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒆𝒏𝒔𝒖𝒓𝒆𝒔 𝒕𝒉𝒂𝒕 𝒊𝒏𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒖𝒂𝒍𝒔 𝒉𝒂𝒗𝒆 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝒓𝒊𝒈𝒉𝒕 𝒕𝒐 𝒔𝒆𝒆𝒌 𝒂 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆 𝒘𝒉𝒆𝒏 𝒕𝒉𝒆𝒊𝒓 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒓𝒊𝒂𝒈𝒆 𝒉𝒂𝒔 𝒃𝒆𝒄𝒐𝒎𝒆 𝒖𝒏𝒕𝒆𝒏𝒂𝒃𝒍𝒆. 𝑰𝒕 𝒔𝒂𝒇𝒆𝒈𝒖𝒂𝒓𝒅𝒔 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒓𝒊𝒈𝒉𝒕𝒔 𝒐𝒇 𝒊𝒏𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒖𝒂𝒍𝒔 𝒕𝒐 𝒎𝒂𝒌𝒆 𝒄𝒉𝒐𝒊𝒄𝒆𝒔 𝒓𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒓𝒅𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒕𝒉𝒆𝒊𝒓 𝒑𝒆𝒓𝒔𝒐𝒏𝒂𝒍 𝒓𝒆𝒍𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏𝒔𝒉𝒊𝒑𝒔 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒘𝒆𝒍𝒍-𝒃𝒆𝒊𝒏𝒈.

3. 𝑹𝒆𝒔𝒐𝒍𝒖𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒐𝒇 𝑴𝒂𝒓𝒊𝒕𝒂𝒍 𝑫𝒊𝒔𝒑𝒖𝒕𝒆𝒔:
 
- 𝑻𝒉𝒆 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆 𝒃𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒐𝒇𝒇𝒆𝒓𝒔 𝒂 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝒂𝒗𝒆𝒏𝒖𝒆 𝒇𝒐𝒓 𝒓𝒆𝒔𝒐𝒍𝒗𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒊𝒕𝒂𝒍 𝒅𝒊𝒔𝒑𝒖𝒕𝒆𝒔 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒄𝒐𝒏𝒇𝒍𝒊𝒄𝒕𝒔 𝒕𝒉𝒂𝒕 𝒄𝒂𝒏𝒏𝒐𝒕 𝒃𝒆 𝒓𝒆𝒄𝒐𝒏𝒄𝒊𝒍𝒆𝒅. 𝑰𝒕 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒆𝒔 𝒂 𝒇𝒐𝒓𝒎𝒂𝒍𝒊𝒛𝒆𝒅 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒄𝒆𝒔𝒔 𝒇𝒐𝒓 𝒂𝒅𝒅𝒓𝒆𝒔𝒔𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒊𝒔𝒔𝒖𝒆𝒔 𝒔𝒖𝒄𝒉 𝒂𝒔 𝒄𝒖𝒔𝒕𝒐𝒅𝒚, 𝒔𝒖𝒑𝒑𝒐𝒓𝒕, 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒊𝒔𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒐𝒇 𝒂𝒔𝒔𝒆𝒕𝒔 𝒊𝒏 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒆𝒗𝒆𝒏𝒕 𝒐𝒇 𝒂 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆.

postTitle: The House of Representatives approves on second reading HB 9349, which seeks to reinstitute absolute divorce as an alternative mode for the dissolution of marriage. | via Willard Cheng, ABS-CBN News
text:
Anne Marie 
Tama naman, pero mamili ka kung isa kang battered wife at wala kang option kundi ang umalis sa impyernong pagsasama. Mas nanaisin mo bang tiisin ang lahat kahit buhay mo o dignidad ang nakasalalay? May point is, oo nga dapat natin sundin ang sampung (10) utos ng diyos. Pero d'ba, binigyan din tayo ng diyos ng kalayaan upang magdesisyon sa buhay at iligtas ang sarili sa bawat suliranin na dadanasin natin? Sa bawat gawa ng tao. Binabalanse pa din ng kalangitan ang magiging kapalaran ng bawat isa sa atin. Kaya naman, kung meron kang bagay na nais mong naisin at ito ay para sa iyong kaligtasan ng buhay kasama ng iyong mga anak laban sa mapanakit mong asawa. Kapayapaan lang naman ang nais ng bawat may buhay sa mundo. Mapagbigay ang panginoon. Kaya hindi nya ipipilit ang bagay na alam nyang ikapapahamak ng isang mabuting tao. Kung nilabag man sa sampung utos. Ito ay babalansehin pa din niya at titimbangin ang mga mabubuti mong nagawa ksa sa masama. 
Dahil walang sinoman tao ang nakakasunod sa sampung utos ng diyos. Ni isa sa bawat tao. May nilalabag sa bawat araw na pamumuhay nya sa mundong ito. Ang 10 commandments mula sa diyos ay isang pag-uutos na maging gabay na may dapat sundin ngunit nasa sa atin pa din kung magagawa mo ito ng perpekto sa buong henerasyon ng pamumuhay mo sa mundong ito.

text: Moses Urmenita Fajardo "Freedom" in divorce refers to the legal concept that allows individuals to dissolve their marriage and gain independence from their spouse. When a couple decides to divorce, they are seeking the freedom to end their marital relationship and live separately. This process involves various legal procedures to divide assets, determine child custody and support, and settle other issues related to the marriage. Ultimately, divorce provides individuals with the freedom to move on from a relationship that is no longer working and start anew.

postTitle: The House of Representatives approves on second reading HB 9349, which seeks to reinstitute absolute divorce as an alternative mode for the dissolution of marriage. | via Willard Cheng, ABS-CBN News
text:
Val Cano In Christianity, divorce is a complex issue. While the Bible acknowledges divorce in certain circumstances, it's generally viewed as a last resort.

In some interpretations of biblical teachings, divorce is permitted in cases of adultery or abandonment (Matthew 19:9). However, reconciliation and forgiveness are encouraged whenever possible.

If reconciliation isn't possible, seeking a divorce may be necessary for both parties to find healing and move forward in their lives. While divorce is a difficult decision, it's crucial to prioritize emotional well-being and seek guidance from trusted spiritual advisors.

Divorce isn't inherently good for kids, but in some cases, it can be a better option than staying in a toxic or unhealthy household. It can provide relief from ongoing conflict, reduce exposure to negative interactions between parents, and create opportunities for children to have more stable and nurturing environments.

Please be open-minded and don't be naive. This bill will not ruin happy families and good marriages. This bill is to give freedom to those who are suffering from abusive marriages. Not for those who are happily married.

postTitle: The House of Representatives approves on second reading HB 9349, which seeks to reinstitute absolute divorce as an alternative mode for the dissolution of marriage. | via Willard Cheng, ABS-CBN News
text:
Rafael Estrobo Jr. bilang isang pro-divorce advocate, gusto kong magalang na maglahad ng kontra-salaysay sa mga sipi na iyong ibinahagi. 

Una, habang binibigyang-diin ng Mateo 19:6-9 at Mateo 5:32 ang kabanalan ng kasal, mahalagang tandaan na kinikilala din nila ang mga pangyayari kung saan pinahihintulutan ang diborsiyo, partikular sa mga kaso ng pakikiapid. Itinatampok nito na kahit sa loob ng mga turo ng Bibliya, may pagkilala na ang ilang sitwasyon ay maaaring mangailangan ng dissolution ng kasal. 

Tungkol sa pag-aangkin na ang pagsuporta sa diborsiyo ay gumagawa ng isa na kasabwat sa kasalanan ng bawat diborsiyado na mag-asawa, mahalagang tandaan na ang pagtataguyod para sa diborsyo ay hindi nangangahulugang hinihikayat ito. Ito ay tungkol sa pagbibigay ng opsyon para sa mga nasa mga sitwasyon kung saan ang pananatili sa kasal ay maaaring magdulot ng higit na pinsala kaysa sa kabutihan. Ito ay tungkol sa pagtataguyod para sa karapatan ng mga indibidwal na piliin kung ano ang pinakamainam para sa kanila. 

Tungkol sa Mga Taga-Corinto 7:32-35, mahalagang tandaan na  ang talata ay nagpapayo sa mga indibidwal na mamuhay nang walang pag-aalala at tumuon sa kaluguran ng Diyos. Gayunpaman, hindi nito tahasang kinokondena ang kasal o diborsyo. Sinasabi lamang nito na ang mga walang asawa ay may mas kaunting makamundong alalahanin. Hindi ito nangangahulugan na masama ang pag-aasawa, ngunit ito ay may sariling hanay ng mga responsibilidad at alalahanin. 

Sa wakas, mahalagang tandaan din na ang mga interpretasyon ng mga relihiyosong teksto ay maaaring mag-iba nang malaki. Kung ano ang nakikita ng isang tao bilang isang ganap na panuntunan, maaaring makita ng isa bilang isang gabay o isang produkto ng makasaysayang konteksto nito. Ang pagtataguyod para sa diborsyo ay hindi nangangahulugan ng pagtanggi sa mga turong ito, ngunit sa halip ay bigyang-kahulugan ang mga ito sa paraang isinasaalang-alang ang mga kumplikado ng modernong buhay at mga relasyon ng tao.

postTitle: The House of Representatives approves on second reading HB 9349, which seeks to reinstitute absolute divorce as an alternative mode for the dissolution of marriage. | via Willard Cheng, ABS-CBN News
text:
Rafael Estrobo Jr. It's great that you're seeking different perspectives on the issue of implementing absolute divorce in the Philippines. Here are some counterarguments to the narratives you mentioned:
 
1. "We are the only ones in this part of the world who have not yet divorced."
 
- Just because other countries have implemented divorce laws doesn't mean it's the best decision for our society. Each country has its own unique cultural and societal values, and it's important to consider what aligns with our own values and beliefs.
 
2. "We have very strong religious faith and believe in the Church and the sanctity of marriage."
 
- While religious beliefs are important to many people, it's essential to recognize that not everyone shares the same religious views. Implementing divorce laws does not undermine the importance of marriage or religious beliefs. It simply provides an option for individuals who are in irreparable and unhealthy relationships.
 
3. "Divorce will lead to blended/dysfunctional families."
 
- While divorce may lead to changes in family dynamics, it's important to note that staying in an unhappy or abusive marriage can also have negative effects on children and the overall well-being of the family. Divorce can provide a fresh start for individuals and the opportunity to create healthier and happier family environments.
 
4. "Married couples will break up immediately after their shared feelings and loneliness fade away."
 
- Divorce is not a decision that couples take lightly. It is a legal process that involves careful consideration and often includes counseling and mediation. While some marriages may end due to changing feelings, many divorces occur because of irreconcilable differences or unhealthy relationship dynamics.
 
5. "Mothers who become overweight after giving birth will be replaced with a younger one."
 
- This narrative implies that divorce is solely based on physical appearance, which is not accurate. Divorce is a complex decision that involves various factors, such as compatibility, communication, and emotional well-being. It is unfair to reduce the reasons for divorce to superficial reasons like physical appearance.
 
Ultimately, the decision to support or oppose the implementation of absolute divorce in the Philippines is a personal one. It's important to consider different perspectives, gather information, and reflect on what aligns with your own values and beliefs. Remember to listen to your heart and make a decision that you believe will contribute to a healthier and happier society. 🌟

text:
Rafael Estrobo Jr. While the perspective that "God hates divorce" and encourages individuals to work on their marriages is rooted in certain religious beliefs, it is important to acknowledge that divorce is a complex and personal matter that may be necessary in certain circumstances.
 
A counter narrative to the statement could be that every individual has the right to prioritize their own well-being and happiness. In situations where a marriage is unhealthy, abusive, or irreparable despite efforts to reconcile, divorce can be a means of seeking safety, healing, and a fresh start.
 
Additionally, it is essential to recognize that not all marriages are centered on a shared commitment to a higher power, and individuals may have valid reasons for ending a marriage that go beyond religious considerations. Each person's journey and decisions regarding divorce should be respected without judgment or condemnation.
 
Ultimately, while religious beliefs can provide guidance and support in relationships, it is crucial to approach the topic of divorce with empathy, understanding, and a recognition of the complexities involved in such a significant life decision.

postTitle: The House of Representatives approves on second reading HB 9349, which seeks to reinstitute absolute divorce as an alternative mode for the dissolution of marriage. | via Willard Cheng, ABS-CBN News
text:
Moses Urmenita Fajardo 
I am a Roman Catholic. Pero in our generations. Di'na pwedeng ipilit pa ang mag asawang hindi na talaga magkasundo. Madaling sabihin sa inyo na you don't agree pero sa large percentage ng mga kababaihan na nahihirapan sa kanilang naging asawa eh hindi sila makawala. Nakita mismo ng dalawang mata ko ang hirap na dinanas ng nanay ko sa ama ko. Pero wala syang magawa dahil kasal sila. Wala kayong karapatan na gamitin ang pangalan ng diyos nag dahil lang sa pagpipigil ninyo ng mga ganitong sistema. Oo pinagbuklod ng diyos. Pero tayo ay nasa mundo at batas ng sangkatauahan ang ginagalawan natin sa panahon ngayon. Walang evil dito dahil sariling pag iisip natin lahat ang meron tayo. Agree ako sa divorce at tayo ay binigyan ng diyos ng kalayaan upang maging malaya sa sarili nating paraan. Katulad ng mga sinabi ni Moises sa huling araw nya sa mundo para sa mga taga israelita. God bless sa atin lahat.

𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐠𝐫𝐨𝐮𝐧𝐝𝐬 𝐟𝐨𝐫 𝐚𝐛𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐮𝐧𝐝𝐞𝐫 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐛𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐢𝐧𝐜𝐥𝐮𝐝𝐞 𝐬𝐢𝐭𝐮𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬 𝐰𝐡𝐞𝐫𝐞 𝐬𝐩𝐨𝐮𝐬𝐞𝐬 𝐡𝐚𝐯𝐞 𝐛𝐞𝐞𝐧 𝐬𝐞𝐩𝐚𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐝 𝐟𝐨𝐫 𝐚𝐭 𝐥𝐞𝐚𝐬𝐭 𝐟𝐢𝐯𝐞 𝐲𝐞𝐚𝐫𝐬 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐫𝐞𝐜𝐨𝐧𝐜𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐢𝐬 𝐡𝐢𝐠𝐡𝐥𝐲 𝐢𝐦𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐛𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞, 𝐨𝐫 𝐢𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞𝐲 𝐡𝐚𝐯𝐞 𝐛𝐞𝐞𝐧 𝐥𝐞𝐠𝐚𝐥𝐥𝐲 𝐬𝐞𝐩𝐚𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐝 𝐛𝐲 𝐥𝐚𝐰.
𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐒𝐞𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐞 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬 𝐡𝐚𝐬 𝐛𝐞𝐞𝐧 𝐢𝐧𝐯𝐨𝐥𝐯𝐞𝐝 𝐢𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐬𝐜𝐮𝐬𝐬𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐀𝐜𝐭 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬, 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐒𝐞𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐞 𝐁𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐍𝐨. 𝟐𝟑𝟕 𝐟𝐢𝐥𝐞𝐝 𝐨𝐧 𝐉𝐮𝐥𝐲 𝟕, 𝟐𝟎𝟐𝟐, 𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐯𝐢𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐟𝐨𝐫 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐬𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐦𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞.
𝐈𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝟏𝟕𝐭𝐡 𝐂𝐨𝐧𝐠𝐫𝐞𝐬𝐬 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐑𝐞𝐩𝐮𝐛𝐥𝐢𝐜, 𝐇𝐨𝐮𝐬𝐞 𝐁𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐍𝐨. 𝟕𝟑𝟎𝟑 𝐰𝐚𝐬 𝐢𝐧𝐭𝐫𝐨𝐝𝐮𝐜𝐞𝐝, 𝐭𝐢𝐭𝐥𝐞𝐝 "𝐀𝐧 𝐀𝐜𝐭 𝐈𝐧𝐬𝐭𝐢𝐭𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐀𝐛𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐞 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐃𝐢𝐬𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐌𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞 𝐢𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬," 𝐚𝐥𝐬𝐨 𝐤𝐧𝐨𝐰𝐧 𝐚𝐬 𝐭𝐡𝐞 "𝐀𝐛𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐞 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐀𝐜𝐭 𝐨𝐟 𝟐𝟎𝟏𝟖."
𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐚𝐩𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐯𝐚𝐥 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐀𝐛𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐞 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐁𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐛𝐲 𝐚 𝐤𝐞𝐲 𝐩𝐚𝐧𝐞𝐥 𝐢𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬 𝐦𝐚𝐫𝐤𝐬 𝐚 𝐬𝐢𝐠𝐧𝐢𝐟𝐢𝐜𝐚𝐧𝐭 𝐬𝐭𝐞𝐩 𝐭𝐨𝐰𝐚𝐫𝐝𝐬 𝐚𝐥𝐢𝐠𝐧𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐜𝐨𝐮𝐧𝐭𝐫𝐲 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐨𝐭𝐡𝐞𝐫𝐬 𝐭𝐡𝐚𝐭 𝐫𝐞𝐜𝐨𝐠𝐧𝐢𝐳𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐚𝐬 𝐚 𝐥𝐞𝐠𝐚𝐥 𝐨𝐩𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧. 𝐓𝐡𝐢𝐬 𝐛𝐢𝐥𝐥, 𝐚𝐥𝐬𝐨 𝐤𝐧𝐨𝐰𝐧 𝐚𝐬 𝐭𝐡𝐞 "𝐃𝐢𝐬𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐌𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞 𝐀𝐜𝐭," 𝐡𝐚𝐬 𝐠𝐚𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐝 𝐞𝐧𝐝𝐨𝐫𝐬𝐞𝐦𝐞𝐧𝐭 𝐟𝐫𝐨𝐦 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐒𝐞𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐞 𝐂𝐨𝐦𝐦𝐢𝐭𝐭𝐞𝐞 𝐨𝐧 𝐖𝐨𝐦𝐞𝐧, 𝐂𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐝𝐫𝐞𝐧, 𝐅𝐚𝐦𝐢𝐥𝐲 𝐑𝐞𝐥𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬, 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐆𝐞𝐧𝐝𝐞𝐫.
𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐢𝐧𝐭𝐫𝐨𝐝𝐮𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐚𝐧 𝐀𝐛𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐞 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐁𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐢𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬 𝐫𝐞𝐟𝐥𝐞𝐜𝐭𝐬 𝐚 𝐬𝐡𝐢𝐟𝐭 𝐭𝐨𝐰𝐚𝐫𝐝𝐬 𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐯𝐢𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐚 𝐥𝐞𝐠𝐚𝐥 𝐟𝐫𝐚𝐦𝐞𝐰𝐨𝐫𝐤 𝐟𝐨𝐫 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐬𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐦𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞𝐬, 𝐨𝐟𝐟𝐞𝐫𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐚𝐧 𝐚𝐥𝐭𝐞𝐫𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐯𝐞 𝐭𝐨 𝐚𝐦𝐞𝐧𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐨𝐫 𝐫𝐞𝐩𝐞𝐚𝐥𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐞𝐱𝐢𝐬𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐥𝐚𝐰𝐬 𝐨𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐬𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐦𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞𝐬.

text:
TineMae Salonga On a legal note, they have a right naman din kasi once dissolved na ang marriage, magiging single na yung ka-relasyon nila and since single din sila, pwed na makasal and they will no longer be kabets hehe they are officially husband and wife.

As to the criminality or offense, nasa original wife na yun kasi sya naman talaga dapat magre-reklamo at magka-kaso. Kung di nya makasuhan at divorced na sila ng husband nya, ibang usapan na naman yan sa batas.

text:
Ang Divorce ay para sa mga magasawang PAPEL NA LANG ANG NAGTATALI. Ibigay po ntin ang karapatan ng bawat isa na maging malaya sa isang kasal na wala ng patutunguhan. Ang pagsasama na WALA NG PAGIBIG ay di po magiging healthy both sa magasawa maging sa mga anak.

postTitle: The House of Representatives approves on second reading HB 9349, which seeks to reinstitute absolute divorce as an alternative mode for the dissolution of marriage. | via Willard Cheng, ABS-CBN News
text:
Di ko gets bakit kung umasta yung ibang tao, pag nagkaroon ng batas ng divorce pipilitin na lahat ng mag-asawa magdivorce. 🤭 Kung masaya ang pagsasama ng mag-asawa, hindi naman kayo apektado kung maisabatas yan. Pero kung walang ganyan, apektado yung mga hindi makaalis sa patay nang relasyon.

Madali lang kasi sabihing nasa tao yan, kelangan iworkout ang problema. E paano kung hindi naman gusto iworkout ng asawa mo, gulpi sarado ka, harap harapan ka nang niloloko. And hindi lang mga babae ang biktima ha. May mga lalake ring sila ang pinependeho. Ano, hahayaan na lang na ganun angg sitwasyon nila habangbuhay?

Kung maganda ang pagsasama ninyong mag-asawa, then you're blessed. Siguro dapat naman iwish rin natin mapunta sa ganung klaseng relasyon rin yung ibang tao. Na hindi mangyayari kung nakatali sila sa abusadong relasyon.

𝐀 𝐜𝐨𝐮𝐧𝐭𝐞𝐫 𝐧𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐯𝐞 𝐭𝐨 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐬𝐭𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐦𝐞𝐧𝐭 𝐜𝐨𝐮𝐥𝐝 𝐛𝐞 𝐭𝐡𝐚𝐭 𝐞𝐯𝐞𝐫𝐲 𝐢𝐧𝐝𝐢𝐯𝐢𝐝𝐮𝐚𝐥 𝐡𝐚𝐬 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐫𝐢𝐠𝐡𝐭 𝐭𝐨 𝐩𝐫𝐢𝐨𝐫𝐢𝐭𝐢𝐳𝐞 𝐭𝐡𝐞𝐢𝐫 𝐨𝐰𝐧 𝐰𝐞𝐥𝐥-𝐛𝐞𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐡𝐚𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬𝐬. 𝐈𝐧 𝐬𝐢𝐭𝐮𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬 𝐰𝐡𝐞𝐫𝐞 𝐚 𝐦𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞 𝐢𝐬 𝐮𝐧𝐡𝐞𝐚𝐥𝐭𝐡𝐲, 𝐚𝐛𝐮𝐬𝐢𝐯𝐞, 𝐨𝐫 𝐢𝐫𝐫𝐞𝐩𝐚𝐫𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞 𝐝𝐞𝐬𝐩𝐢𝐭𝐞 𝐞𝐟𝐟𝐨𝐫𝐭𝐬 𝐭𝐨 𝐫𝐞𝐜𝐨𝐧𝐜𝐢𝐥𝐞, 𝐝𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐜𝐚𝐧 𝐛𝐞 𝐚 𝐦𝐞𝐚𝐧𝐬 𝐨𝐟 𝐬𝐞𝐞𝐤𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐬𝐚𝐟𝐞𝐭𝐲, 𝐡𝐞𝐚𝐥𝐢𝐧𝐠, 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐚 𝐟𝐫𝐞𝐬𝐡 𝐬𝐭𝐚𝐫𝐭.

𝐄𝐚𝐜𝐡 𝐩𝐞𝐫𝐬𝐨𝐧'𝐬 𝐣𝐨𝐮𝐫𝐧𝐞𝐲 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐝𝐞𝐜𝐢𝐬𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬 𝐫𝐞𝐠𝐚𝐫𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐝𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐬𝐡𝐨𝐮𝐥𝐝 𝐛𝐞 𝐫𝐞𝐬𝐩𝐞𝐜𝐭𝐞𝐝 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡𝐨𝐮𝐭 𝐣𝐮𝐝𝐠𝐦𝐞𝐧𝐭 𝐨𝐫 𝐜𝐨𝐧𝐝𝐞𝐦𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧.
 
𝐔𝐥𝐭𝐢𝐦𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐥𝐲, 𝐰𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐞 𝐫𝐞𝐥𝐢𝐠𝐢𝐨𝐮𝐬 𝐛𝐞𝐥𝐢𝐞𝐟𝐬 𝐜𝐚𝐧 𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐯𝐢𝐝𝐞 𝐠𝐮𝐢𝐝𝐚𝐧𝐜𝐞 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐬𝐮𝐩𝐩𝐨𝐫𝐭 𝐢𝐧 𝐫𝐞𝐥𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬𝐡𝐢𝐩𝐬, 𝐢𝐭 𝐢𝐬 𝐜𝐫𝐮𝐜𝐢𝐚𝐥 𝐭𝐨 𝐚𝐩𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐚𝐜𝐡 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐭𝐨𝐩𝐢𝐜 𝐨𝐟 𝐝𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐞𝐦𝐩𝐚𝐭𝐡𝐲, 𝐮𝐧𝐝𝐞𝐫𝐬𝐭𝐚𝐧𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠, 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐚 𝐫𝐞𝐜𝐨𝐠𝐧𝐢𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐜𝐨𝐦𝐩𝐥𝐞𝐱𝐢𝐭𝐢𝐞𝐬 𝐢𝐧𝐯𝐨𝐥𝐯𝐞𝐝 𝐢𝐧 𝐬𝐮𝐜𝐡 𝐚 𝐬𝐢𝐠𝐧𝐢𝐟𝐢𝐜𝐚𝐧𝐭 𝐥𝐢𝐟𝐞 𝐝𝐞𝐜𝐢𝐬𝐢𝐨𝐧.

6. 𝑷𝒓𝒆𝒗𝒆𝒏𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒐𝒇 𝑳𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝑳𝒐𝒐𝒑𝒉𝒐𝒍𝒆𝒔:
 
- 𝑯𝒂𝒗𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒂 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆 𝒃𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒉𝒆𝒍𝒑𝒔 𝒑𝒓𝒆𝒗𝒆𝒏𝒕 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝒍𝒐𝒐𝒑𝒉𝒐𝒍𝒆𝒔 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒇𝒓𝒂𝒖𝒅𝒖𝒍𝒆𝒏𝒕 𝒑𝒓𝒂𝒄𝒕𝒊𝒄𝒆𝒔 𝒊𝒏 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒅𝒊𝒔𝒔𝒐𝒍𝒖𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒐𝒇 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒓𝒊𝒂𝒈𝒆𝒔. 𝑰𝒕 𝒆𝒔𝒕𝒂𝒃𝒍𝒊𝒔𝒉𝒆𝒔 𝒄𝒍𝒆𝒂𝒓 𝒈𝒖𝒊𝒅𝒆𝒍𝒊𝒏𝒆𝒔 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒄𝒓𝒊𝒕𝒆𝒓𝒊𝒂 𝒇𝒐𝒓 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆, 𝒓𝒆𝒅𝒖𝒄𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒑𝒐𝒕𝒆𝒏𝒕𝒊𝒂𝒍 𝒇𝒐𝒓 𝒂𝒃𝒖𝒔𝒆 𝒐𝒓 𝒎𝒂𝒏𝒊𝒑𝒖𝒍𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒐𝒇 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝒔𝒚𝒔𝒕𝒆𝒎.
 
𝑶𝒗𝒆𝒓𝒂𝒍𝒍, 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒆𝒔𝒔𝒆𝒏𝒄𝒆 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒊𝒎𝒑𝒐𝒓𝒕𝒂𝒏𝒄𝒆 𝒐𝒇 𝒉𝒂𝒗𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒂 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆 𝒃𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒊𝒏 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝑷𝒉𝒊𝒍𝒊𝒑𝒑𝒊𝒏𝒆𝒔 𝒓𝒆𝒗𝒐𝒍𝒗𝒆 𝒂𝒓𝒐𝒖𝒏𝒅 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒂 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝒂𝒗𝒆𝒏𝒖𝒆 𝒇𝒐𝒓 𝒄𝒐𝒖𝒑𝒍𝒆𝒔 𝒕𝒐 𝒆𝒏𝒅 𝒊𝒓𝒓𝒆𝒕𝒓𝒊𝒆𝒗𝒂𝒃𝒍𝒚 𝒃𝒓𝒐𝒌𝒆𝒏 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒓𝒊𝒂𝒈𝒆𝒔, 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒕𝒆𝒄𝒕𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒊𝒏𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒖𝒂𝒍𝒔' 𝒓𝒊𝒈𝒉𝒕𝒔, 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒎𝒐𝒕𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒆𝒎𝒐𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏𝒂𝒍 𝒘𝒆𝒍𝒍-𝒃𝒆𝒊𝒏𝒈, 𝒂𝒅𝒗𝒂𝒏𝒄𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒔𝒐𝒄𝒊𝒂𝒍 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒈𝒓𝒆𝒔𝒔, 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒑𝒓𝒆𝒗𝒆𝒏𝒕𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝒂𝒎𝒃𝒊𝒈𝒖𝒊𝒕𝒊𝒆𝒔 𝒊𝒏 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒅𝒊𝒔𝒔𝒐𝒍𝒖𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒐𝒇 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒊𝒕𝒂𝒍 𝒓𝒆𝒍𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏𝒔𝒉𝒊𝒑𝒔.

postTitle: The House of Representatives approves on second reading HB 9349, which seeks to reinstitute absolute divorce as an alternative mode for the dissolution of marriage. | via Willard Cheng, ABS-CBN News
text:
Divorce is our civil right! Regardless of religious beliefs!

While the perspective that "God hates divorce" and encourages individuals to work on their marriages is rooted in certain religious beliefs, it is important to acknowledge that divorce is a complex and personal matter that may be necessary in certain circumstances.

A counter narrative to the statement could be that every individual has the right to prioritize their own well-being and happiness. In situations where a marriage is unhealthy, abusive, or irreparable despite efforts to reconcile, divorce can be a means of seeking safety, healing, and a fresh start.

Additionally, it is essential to recognize that not all marriages are centered on a shared commitment to a higher power, and individuals may have valid reasons for ending a marriage that go beyond religious considerations. Each person's journey and decisions regarding divorce should be respected without judgment or condemnation.

Ultimately, while religious beliefs can provide guidance and support in relationships, it is crucial to approach the topic of divorce with empathy, understanding, and a recognition of the complexities involved in such a significant life decision.

#ReinstituteDivorce
#divorceisourcivilright
#DivorcePilipinas

text:
𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬 𝐡𝐚𝐬 𝐛𝐞𝐞𝐧 𝐜𝐨𝐧𝐬𝐢𝐝𝐞𝐫𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐢𝐧𝐭𝐫𝐨𝐝𝐮𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐚𝐧 𝐀𝐛𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐞 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐁𝐢𝐥𝐥, 𝐰𝐡𝐢𝐜𝐡 𝐰𝐨𝐮𝐥𝐝 𝐚𝐥𝐥𝐨𝐰 𝐟𝐨𝐫 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐥𝐞𝐠𝐚𝐥 𝐭𝐞𝐫𝐦𝐢𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐚 𝐦𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞 𝐛𝐲 𝐚 𝐜𝐨𝐮𝐫𝐭 𝐢𝐧 𝐚 𝐥𝐞𝐠𝐚𝐥 𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐜𝐞𝐞𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠. 𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐠𝐫𝐨𝐮𝐧𝐝𝐬 𝐟𝐨𝐫 𝐚𝐛𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐮𝐧𝐝𝐞𝐫 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐛𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐢𝐧𝐜𝐥𝐮𝐝𝐞 𝐬𝐢𝐭𝐮𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬 𝐰𝐡𝐞𝐫𝐞 𝐬𝐩𝐨𝐮𝐬𝐞𝐬 𝐡𝐚𝐯𝐞 𝐛𝐞𝐞𝐧 𝐬𝐞𝐩𝐚𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐝 𝐟𝐨𝐫 𝐚𝐭 𝐥𝐞𝐚𝐬𝐭 𝐟𝐢𝐯𝐞 𝐲𝐞𝐚𝐫𝐬 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐫𝐞𝐜𝐨𝐧𝐜𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐢𝐬 𝐡𝐢𝐠𝐡𝐥𝐲 𝐢𝐦𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐛𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞, 𝐨𝐫 𝐢𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞𝐲 𝐡𝐚𝐯𝐞 𝐛𝐞𝐞𝐧 𝐥𝐞𝐠𝐚𝐥𝐥𝐲 𝐬𝐞𝐩𝐚𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐝 𝐛𝐲 𝐥𝐚𝐰.
𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐒𝐞𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐞 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬 𝐡𝐚𝐬 𝐛𝐞𝐞𝐧 𝐢𝐧𝐯𝐨𝐥𝐯𝐞𝐝 𝐢𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐬𝐜𝐮𝐬𝐬𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐀𝐜𝐭 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬, 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐒𝐞𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐞 𝐁𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐍𝐨. 𝟐𝟑𝟕 𝐟𝐢𝐥𝐞𝐝 𝐨𝐧 𝐉𝐮𝐥𝐲 𝟕, 𝟐𝟎𝟐𝟐, 𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐯𝐢𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐟𝐨𝐫 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐬𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐦𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞.
𝐈𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝟏𝟕𝐭𝐡 𝐂𝐨𝐧𝐠𝐫𝐞𝐬𝐬 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐑𝐞𝐩𝐮𝐛𝐥𝐢𝐜, 𝐇𝐨𝐮𝐬𝐞 𝐁𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐍𝐨. 𝟕𝟑𝟎𝟑 𝐰𝐚𝐬 𝐢𝐧𝐭𝐫𝐨𝐝𝐮𝐜𝐞𝐝, 𝐭𝐢𝐭𝐥𝐞𝐝 "𝐀𝐧 𝐀𝐜𝐭 𝐈𝐧𝐬𝐭𝐢𝐭𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐀𝐛𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐞 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐃𝐢𝐬𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐌𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞 𝐢𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬," 𝐚𝐥𝐬𝐨 𝐤𝐧𝐨𝐰𝐧 𝐚𝐬 𝐭𝐡𝐞 "𝐀𝐛𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐞 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐀𝐜𝐭 𝐨𝐟 𝟐𝟎𝟏𝟖."
𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐚𝐩𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐯𝐚𝐥 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐀𝐛𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐞 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐁𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐛𝐲 𝐚 𝐤𝐞𝐲 𝐩𝐚𝐧𝐞𝐥 𝐢𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬 𝐦𝐚𝐫𝐤𝐬 𝐚 𝐬𝐢𝐠𝐧𝐢𝐟𝐢𝐜𝐚𝐧𝐭 𝐬𝐭𝐞𝐩 𝐭𝐨𝐰𝐚𝐫𝐝𝐬 𝐚𝐥𝐢𝐠𝐧𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐜𝐨𝐮𝐧𝐭𝐫𝐲 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐨𝐭𝐡𝐞𝐫𝐬 𝐭𝐡𝐚𝐭 𝐫𝐞𝐜𝐨𝐠𝐧𝐢𝐳𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐚𝐬 𝐚 𝐥𝐞𝐠𝐚𝐥 𝐨𝐩𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧. 𝐓𝐡𝐢𝐬 𝐛𝐢𝐥𝐥, 𝐚𝐥𝐬𝐨 𝐤𝐧𝐨𝐰𝐧 𝐚𝐬 𝐭𝐡𝐞 "𝐃𝐢𝐬𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐌𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞 𝐀𝐜𝐭," 𝐡𝐚𝐬 𝐠𝐚𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐝 𝐞𝐧𝐝𝐨𝐫𝐬𝐞𝐦𝐞𝐧𝐭 𝐟𝐫𝐨𝐦 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐒𝐞𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐞 𝐂𝐨𝐦𝐦𝐢𝐭𝐭𝐞𝐞 𝐨𝐧 𝐖𝐨𝐦𝐞𝐧, 𝐂𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐝𝐫𝐞𝐧, 𝐅𝐚𝐦𝐢𝐥𝐲 𝐑𝐞𝐥𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬, 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐆𝐞𝐧𝐝𝐞𝐫.
𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐢𝐧𝐭𝐫𝐨𝐝𝐮𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐚𝐧 𝐀𝐛𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐞 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐨𝐫𝐜𝐞 𝐁𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐢𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐩𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬 𝐫𝐞𝐟𝐥𝐞𝐜𝐭𝐬 𝐚 𝐬𝐡𝐢𝐟𝐭 𝐭𝐨𝐰𝐚𝐫𝐝𝐬 𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐯𝐢𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐚 𝐥𝐞𝐠𝐚𝐥 𝐟𝐫𝐚𝐦𝐞𝐰𝐨𝐫𝐤 𝐟𝐨𝐫 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐬𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐦𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞𝐬, 𝐨𝐟𝐟𝐞𝐫𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐚𝐧 𝐚𝐥𝐭𝐞𝐫𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐯𝐞 𝐭𝐨 𝐚𝐦𝐞𝐧𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐨𝐫 𝐫𝐞𝐩𝐞𝐚𝐥𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐞𝐱𝐢𝐬𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐥𝐚𝐰𝐬 𝐨𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐝𝐢𝐬𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐨𝐟 𝐦𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐠𝐞𝐬.

postTitle: The House of Representatives approves on second reading HB 9349, which seeks to reinstitute absolute divorce as an alternative mode for the dissolution of marriage. | via Willard Cheng, ABS-CBN News
text:
𝑻𝒉𝒆 𝒆𝒔𝒔𝒆𝒏𝒄𝒆 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒊𝒎𝒑𝒐𝒓𝒕𝒂𝒏𝒄𝒆 𝒐𝒇 𝒉𝒂𝒗𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒂 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆 𝒃𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒊𝒏 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝑷𝒉𝒊𝒍𝒊𝒑𝒑𝒊𝒏𝒆𝒔 𝒍𝒊𝒆 𝒊𝒏 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒂 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝒇𝒓𝒂𝒎𝒆𝒘𝒐𝒓𝒌 𝒕𝒉𝒂𝒕 𝒓𝒆𝒄𝒐𝒈𝒏𝒊𝒛𝒆𝒔 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒂𝒅𝒅𝒓𝒆𝒔𝒔𝒆𝒔 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒄𝒐𝒎𝒑𝒍𝒆𝒙𝒊𝒕𝒊𝒆𝒔 𝒐𝒇 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒊𝒕𝒂𝒍 𝒓𝒆𝒍𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏𝒔𝒉𝒊𝒑𝒔 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒐𝒇𝒇𝒆𝒓𝒔 𝒂 𝒇𝒐𝒓𝒎𝒂𝒍 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒄𝒆𝒔𝒔 𝒇𝒐𝒓 𝒄𝒐𝒖𝒑𝒍𝒆𝒔 𝒕𝒐 𝒅𝒊𝒔𝒔𝒐𝒍𝒗𝒆 𝒕𝒉𝒆𝒊𝒓 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒓𝒊𝒂𝒈𝒆 𝒘𝒉𝒆𝒏 𝒓𝒆𝒄𝒐𝒏𝒄𝒊𝒍𝒊𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒊𝒔 𝒏𝒐 𝒍𝒐𝒏𝒈𝒆𝒓 𝒇𝒆𝒂𝒔𝒊𝒃𝒍𝒆. 𝑺𝒐𝒎𝒆 𝒌𝒆𝒚 𝒑𝒐𝒊𝒏𝒕𝒔 𝒉𝒊𝒈𝒉𝒍𝒊𝒈𝒉𝒕𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒆𝒔𝒔𝒆𝒏𝒄𝒆 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒊𝒎𝒑𝒐𝒓𝒕𝒂𝒏𝒄𝒆 𝒐𝒇 𝒉𝒂𝒗𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒂 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆 𝒃𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒊𝒏 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝑷𝒉𝒊𝒍𝒊𝒑𝒑𝒊𝒏𝒆𝒔 𝒊𝒏𝒄𝒍𝒖𝒅𝒆:
 
1. 𝑳𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝑹𝒆𝒄𝒐𝒈𝒏𝒊𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒐𝒇 𝑴𝒂𝒓𝒊𝒕𝒂𝒍 𝑫𝒊𝒔𝒔𝒐𝒍𝒖𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏:
 
- 𝑨 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆 𝒃𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒂𝒄𝒌𝒏𝒐𝒘𝒍𝒆𝒅𝒈𝒆𝒔 𝒕𝒉𝒂𝒕 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒓𝒊𝒂𝒈𝒆𝒔 𝒄𝒂𝒏 𝒊𝒓𝒓𝒆𝒕𝒓𝒊𝒆𝒗𝒂𝒃𝒍𝒚 𝒃𝒓𝒆𝒂𝒌 𝒅𝒐𝒘𝒏, 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒕𝒉𝒆𝒓𝒆 𝒊𝒔 𝒂 𝒏𝒆𝒆𝒅 𝒇𝒐𝒓 𝒂 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝒎𝒆𝒄𝒉𝒂𝒏𝒊𝒔𝒎 𝒕𝒐 𝒇𝒐𝒓𝒎𝒂𝒍𝒍𝒚 𝒆𝒏𝒅 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒊𝒕𝒂𝒍 𝒓𝒆𝒍𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏𝒔𝒉𝒊𝒑. 𝑰𝒕 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒆𝒔 𝒂 𝒔𝒕𝒓𝒖𝒄𝒕𝒖𝒓𝒆𝒅 𝒑𝒓𝒐𝒄𝒆𝒔𝒔 𝒇𝒐𝒓 𝒄𝒐𝒖𝒑𝒍𝒆𝒔 𝒕𝒐 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍𝒍𝒚 𝒔𝒆𝒑𝒂𝒓𝒂𝒕𝒆 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒎𝒐𝒗𝒆 𝒐𝒏 𝒘𝒊𝒕𝒉 𝒕𝒉𝒆𝒊𝒓 𝒍𝒊𝒗𝒆𝒔.

2. 𝑷𝒓𝒐𝒕𝒆𝒄𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒐𝒇 𝑰𝒏𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒖𝒂𝒍𝒔' 𝑹𝒊𝒈𝒉𝒕𝒔:
 
- 𝑯𝒂𝒗𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒂 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆 𝒃𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒆𝒏𝒔𝒖𝒓𝒆𝒔 𝒕𝒉𝒂𝒕 𝒊𝒏𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒖𝒂𝒍𝒔 𝒉𝒂𝒗𝒆 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒍𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒍 𝒓𝒊𝒈𝒉𝒕 𝒕𝒐 𝒔𝒆𝒆𝒌 𝒂 𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒐𝒓𝒄𝒆 𝒘𝒉𝒆𝒏 𝒕𝒉𝒆𝒊𝒓 𝒎𝒂𝒓𝒓𝒊𝒂𝒈𝒆 𝒉𝒂𝒔 𝒃𝒆𝒄𝒐𝒎𝒆 𝒖𝒏𝒕𝒆𝒏𝒂𝒃𝒍𝒆. 𝑰𝒕 𝒔𝒂𝒇𝒆𝒈𝒖𝒂𝒓𝒅𝒔 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒓𝒊𝒈𝒉𝒕𝒔 𝒐𝒇 𝒊𝒏𝒅𝒊𝒗𝒊𝒅𝒖𝒂𝒍𝒔 𝒕𝒐 𝒎𝒂𝒌𝒆 𝒄𝒉𝒐𝒊𝒄𝒆𝒔 𝒓𝒆𝒈𝒂𝒓𝒅𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒕𝒉𝒆𝒊𝒓 𝒑𝒆𝒓𝒔𝒐𝒏𝒂𝒍 𝒓𝒆𝒍𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏𝒔𝒉𝒊𝒑𝒔 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒘𝒆𝒍𝒍-𝒃𝒆𝒊𝒏𝒈.

3. 𝑹𝒆𝒔𝒐𝒍𝒖𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒐𝒇 𝑴𝒂𝒓𝒊𝒕𝒂𝒍 𝑫𝒊𝒔𝒑𝒖𝒕𝒆𝒔:
